message.content:
The start symbol S has only three productions:

1. S → NT64 NT96  
2. S → NT97 NT7  
3. S → NT35 NT84  

To find the first terminal produced by each option, follow the left-most derivation in every branch:

• NT64 can yield either ‘t4’ (directly) or begin with NT84, whose leftmost terminal is always ‘t0’, ‘t1’ or ‘t2’.  
• NT97 can yield ‘t2’ (directly) or start with NT43, which is always ‘t0’.  
• NT35 yields exactly ‘t3’.

Hence the only way to start a string with ‘t3’ is to use the rule S → NT35 NT84.

After this initial ‘t3’, the next symbol must come from NT84.  
But NT84 can produce only

– a single terminal ‘t0’  
– a single terminal ‘t2’  
– or the sequence NT4 NT1, whose first terminal is always NT4 → ‘t1’.

Therefore every string derived via S → NT35 NT84 must begin either

t3 t0…, t3 t2…, or t3 t1…

The given string starts with

t3 t3…

Since ‘t3’ cannot follow the initial ‘t3’ under any derivation of NT84, the grammar cannot generate the provided string.

No

The start symbol S can expand only in one of the following three ways:

1. S → NT64 NT96  
2. S → NT97 NT7  
3. S → NT35 NT84

Because the first word of the string is t4, only the first alternative is possible:

S → NT64 NT96 with NT64 → 't4'

So NT64 produces the first symbol (t4) and all remaining 14 symbols must be generated by NT96.

NT96 has only two kinds of productions:

• NT96 → 't4' | 't3' (1 symbol)  (impossible: we still need 14)  
• NT96 → NT54 NT53

Hence NT96 must use the second rule and the second word of the string must come from NT54, leaving the last 13 words to NT53.

NT54 can give exactly one terminal, chosen from {t1, t3, t4}.  
The second word of the string is t1, so we must take NT54 → 't1'.

Thus NT53 must generate the 13-symbol tail

t1 t3 t4 t4 t2 t4 t0 t4 t1 t2 t2 t0 t2

NT53 can expand only as

a) NT53 → NT86 NT33 (puts t0 first)  
b) NT53 → NT39 NT80 (puts the output of NT39 first, then one symbol from NT80)

Case (a) is impossible because it forces the first symbol produced by NT53 to be t0, but the tail starts with t1.

So we need case (b): NT53 → NT39 NT80.  
NT80 is a single terminal, either t2 or t3, and it is always the LAST symbol produced by NT53.

Consequently the 13-symbol tail produced by NT53 must end in either t2 or t3.  
Our tail ends in t2, so that part is fine, but it also contains t3 in the fourth position:

t1 t3 t4 …

The symbols produced by NT39 come from its recursive rule NT39 → NT70 NT39 (eventually ending in NT39 → 't0').  
Every NT70 gives two or three symbols consisting only of {t0, t1, t2, t4}; none of its components (NT84, NT36) can ever yield t3.

Therefore NT39 can never produce any t3 at all.  
Because all of NT53 except the very last symbol comes from NT39, every t3 inside the 13-symbol tail would have to be the final symbol.  
But the tail contains a t3 in the second position, not at the end, which is impossible.

Hence no derivation can produce the given string, so the string is not in the language of the grammar.

No
